NOTES

1. The patch deliberately writes config.bin BEFORE the legacy-migration
   block. For FIRMWARE_VERSION=0x0010 boards this is a no-op (migration
   only runs when (device_fw & 0xFFF0) != (FIRMWARE_VERSION & 0xFFF0)),
   but writing pre-migration is the right semantics: the fixture is the
   raw bytes the device put on the wire, not the configurator's
   reinterpretation.

2. params.bin is the raw 64-byte HID frame (1 byte report-id + 71 bytes
   payload + 0 padding = 72 used + 0 unused, BUFFERSIZE is 64 so the
   payload extends only as far as the buffer; cross-check against
   FREEJOY_PARAMS_REPORT_SIZE in common_defines.h).

   Hmm — re-check: FREEJOY_PARAMS_REPORT_SIZE = 72 but BUFFERSIZE
   appears to be 64. If the report is truly 72 bytes, hid_read_timeout
   should be reading more than 64. Verify this against the actual
   common_defines.h when reading fixtures. If BUFFERSIZE is too small,
   the dumped params.bin is truncated; either expand BUFFERSIZE in the
   patch or audit how the Qt app currently handles 72-byte reports.

3. The patch uses Qt's QFile rather than std::fstream so the capture
   doesn't add any new platform dependencies; it compiles wherever the
   Qt app already compiles.

4. Throwaway. After capture is complete and fixtures are in the Rust
   repo, discard the patched branch. Do NOT commit this to
   FreeJoyXConfiguratorQt.
